<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading"><strong>FAQs</strong></h2>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li><strong>What=E2=80=99s the best kind of wax to use for homemade candles=
? </strong>Paraffin wax is a common wax used to make candles; however, it=
=E2=80=99s derived from petroleum and not the best natural product. <strong=
>Soy wax and beeswax are both natural waxes</strong> that are inexpensive a=
nd easy to find. Both soy candles and beeswax candles are slow-burning. Soy=
 holds fragrance better than beeswax. But beeswax has its own honey scent, =
which many folks (including myself) find appealing.</li>



<li><strong>Can you reuse old candle jars to make homemade candles?</strong=
> Yes, you can! It=E2=80=99s a great way to save money. Place the used cand=
le jars in the freezer. After a couple of days, remove the jars and gently =
scrape out the old wax and wick. Or, leave the old wax and just remove the =
wick, since you=E2=80=99ll be re-pouring new wax overtop anyway.</li>



<li><strong>The wax cracked on top of my candles. What can I do? </strong>M=
elt a bit more wax and fill in the cracks with the wax. The candles are sti=
ll usable with tunneling or cracks in the wax; it=E2=80=99s just a cosmetic=
 issue.</li>
</ul>



<div class=3D"wp-block-group"><div class=3D"wp-block-group__inner-container=
 is-layout-constrained wp-block-group-is-layout-constrained">
<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"isPasted"><strong>Conclusion: Is it ch=
eaper to make your own candles?</strong></h2>



<p>Yes, it is cheaper to make your own homemade candles, particularly if yo=
u want to use natural candles, made with the highest-quality ingredients li=
ke pure soy and beeswax and quality scents, like essential oils.</p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>A<strong>&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://amzn.to/3re2EpO" target=3D"_blank" re=
l=3D"noreferrer noopener nofollow">16-ounce bag of beeswax</a>&nbsp;</stron=
g>costs about $13 and a<strong>&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://amzn.to/3ufxpwh" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener nofollow">5-lb bag of soy flakes=
</a></strong>&nbsp;costs about $20. Both options will make multiple candles=
. 2 cups of wax =3D 1 8-ounce candle. </li>



<li><strong><a href=3D"https://amzn.to/3LDrJEn" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"no=
follow">Candle wicks</a></strong>&nbsp;will cost about $10, making many can=
dles. You only need 1 wick per jar.</li>



<li><strong>Use leftover jars. </strong>Use extra mason jars, leftover jam =
or candle jars, or thrifted tea cups.</li>



<li><strong>Purchase&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://amzn.to/3rZiALK" target=3D"_bl=
ank" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener nofollow">a tall glass measuring cup</a>, h=
eat-safe mixing bowl, or candle pourer just for melting the wax</strong>, a=
s it will be impossible to clean the wax out of the jar once melted and coo=
led. Reuse this container each time you make candles. <strong>This will cos=
t about $6-10</strong>.</li>



<li>Essential oils or fragrance oils vary in price. Fragrance oils are the =
cheaper options, essential oils can be more expensive. But you can <strong>=
use essential oils to make other cleaning and beauty products</strong>. </l=
i>
</ul>



<p>Even with a $20-30 investment, you can <strong>make many homemade candle=
s</strong>! If you=E2=80=99ve checked the price of natural candles lately, =
you know that=E2=80=99s a deal. Plus, you=E2=80=99ll be able to say =E2=80=
=9CI did this!=E2=80=9D and impress your friends and family (priceless).</p=
>



<p>So tell me, what do you think? Will you try making your own candles, or =
do you prefer store-bought candles?</p>
